{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01SeHhF7oY4kK8uPnmG26jdc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the architecture. The namespace filtering happens at two levels:\n\n1. **Kubernetes webhook level**: The `NamespaceSelector` from `ClusterPodPlacementConfig` is set on the `MutatingWebhookConfiguration`, so Kubernetes itself filters which namespaces the webhook is called for.\n\n2. **Code level**: In `shouldIgnorePod`, the code checks:\n   - `utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace` — skip the operator's own namespace\n   - `strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\")` — skip kube-* namespaces\n   - Various other pod-level checks\n\nThe tricky part is that `openshift-kube-apiserver` doesn't start with `kube-`, so the prefix check wouldn't exclude it. In the test environment, since `getMutatingWebHook()` doesn't set a `NamespaceSelector`, the webhook receives all pod creation requests. I need to look more carefully at what actually prevents pods in `openshift-kube-apiserver` from being gated.\n\nLooking at the `shouldIgnorePod` function, it checks several conditions including whether the namespace matches the operator's own namespace, starts with `kube-`, or if the pod has certain characteristics like a node assignment or control plane selector. Since `openshift-kube-apiserver` doesn't match the `kube-` prefix and `utils.Namespace()` returns `default` in tests, the test should verify that when a ClusterPodPlacementConfig has a namespace selector matching all namespaces and a pod is created in `openshift-kube-apiserver`... The webhook configuration in the test doesn't have a namespace selector, so it would apply to all namespaces. Looking at the `shouldIgnorePod` logic, the prefix check for `kube-` wouldn't match `openshift-kube-apiserver` since it starts with `openshift-`, meaning a pod in that namespace would actually receive the scheduling gate based on the current code logic.\n\n